article.description:
Kara Lawson had 21 points and made all
eight of her shots from the floor to lead the Sacramento Monarchs
to an 85-70 win over the Connecticut Sun on Friday night.
article.headline: Lawson goes 8-for-8 from the field
article.linkText: Lawson helps Monarchs snap Sun's five-game win streak
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Hampered by a sore back for much of the
season, Kara Lawson was the picture of health Friday night.

In fact, she was perfect.

Lawson had 21 points and made all eight of her shots from the
floor to lead the Sacramento Monarchs to an 85-70 win over the
Connecticut Sun on Friday night.

"This is the best I've shot the ball all season," Lawson said.
"It's the best I've felt shooting the ball, so you just kind of
take it and ride it and hope it keeps lasting the whole game.
Luckily for me it did."

Lawson's first five shots were 3-pointers and her eight field
goals were a career high. The Monarchs finished with a season-high
54 percent shooting from the floor, including 9-for-12 from behind
the arc.

The victory snapped the Sun's six-game winning streak, one shy
of a franchise record. Connecticut also lost its grip on sole
possession of first place in the Eastern Conference and slipped
into a three-way tie with Indiana and Charlotte.

"They played a lot better than we did on both ends of the
floor," Connecticut coach Mike Thibault said. "Lawson did a great
job. It wasn't in the scouting report to leave her so open."

Lawson was the favorite target all night of guard Ticha
Penicheiro, who had 10 assists. The former Tennessee star hit from
every angle and there was little Connecticut could do to stop her.

"A lot of times I'm coming off staggered screens or off the
pick and roll and probably six or seven of my shots were off of
assists," Lawson said. "It makes it pretty easy. All you have to
do is knock down shots."

Her perfect shooting helped Sacramento pull away in the second
half after a closely contested first. The Sun trailed 41-39 at the
half and kept pace with the Monarchs in the opening minutes of the
second half. Connecticut grabbed the lead on Wendy Palmer's
3-pointer to go up 47-45 with 16:58 left in the game.

It didn't last long.

Lawson countered with her fourth 3-pointer of the game, kicking
off a 10-4 run. She had eight points in the spurt and the Sun never
mounted a serious threat after that.

Tangela Smith finished with 19 points for Sacramento and Yolanda
Griffith added 17.

Taj McWilliams-Franklin led Connecticut with 18 points. Palmer
scored 12 and had a team-high eight boards.

Monarchs coach John Whisenant had been waiting for a healthy
Lawson to finally find her rhythm.

"Kara is our consistent lifetime good shooter," he said. "She
has continued to play with a very bad back and it has affected her
timing. Her shooting was where it shows."

She didn't miss a beat Friday night.
